segments.text: little concerned about the professionalism about about your colleague uh... you know all we're still in business to make money to make a living and so a certain amount of competition is good for everybody but some of the things that are happening are are you know not very uh... i think they're dragging us down in our own eyes even yeah and that's the bad part what you're saying is we've met the enemy and he is us it's not what the public perceives us as much as it is what we perceive ourselves
Don't you think we've met the enemy and he's us?
Oh, yeah.
No question.
That's a good point.
I'm serious.
There's no question about that.
But we had no course addressed to jurisprudence.
Well, we had one course.
They had a one-hour course, veterinary jurisprudence, and it was neat.
It gave you just a little smattering of legality with veterinary medicine.
We had nothing.
And they had nothing.
Did you have anything, Tom?
No.
When I came back here, he only had a jurisprudence test.
Oh, he just retired, just died.
Just died, yeah.
Stewart.
Judge Stewart.
In College Station.
He was an attorney that taught the one-hour veterinary jurisprudence court.
I'll tell you, students are going to need it now.
Oh, boy.
And they are.
It's a different world out there.
It really is.
It really is.
Like I said, we were too busy working to be good businessmen.
You know, we did business courses and jurisprudence courses and more.
Well, and the other thing that's happening in this whole thing, the other thing that's happening in this whole thing.
Has been real helpful to us in animal control.
He comes and gives us, yeah, he's done a lot.
Oh, he has a manuscript about like this of different cases that have come up involving animals, crime, and so forth.
No, I'm just sitting here thinking, you know, about 12 of the veterinarians that were here when we first came.
Only three of them are even here, or even alive.
Well, there was Wharton, there was Walt Lawrence, there was Al Nagel, Charlie Neal, Richard Culpepper, R.D.
Brown, Gerald Parker, Harry Fladigal, Ray, Johnny McCannish, Pinky Houser, Charlie Neal.
And all that's left is Al.
R.D., Gerald, you and me.
You know that R.D.
and Gerald are both in the hospital.
Are they really?
R.D.
and Gerald, both?
R.D.
's just getting his diabetes stabilized.
They've been there over a week, though.
And Gerald, they rushed him in the middle of the morning, in the wee hours.
He passed out completely.
They think it's enough.
That's right.
Well, no, Jim came after him.
Where was Jim Saunders?
No, he graduated.
He graduated in 41.
Yeah, he was.
Was he in San Antonio?
Was he in San Antonio at that time?
He came in 56.
See, that's the reason.
You know, one of the other things that is happening today that has affected me in a case is that veterinarians now, a lot of the younger veterinarians they're getting out,
And again, in their zeal, I think, probably to be successful, are not using the wisdom that they should use about commenting on other veterinarians' treatments.
And I had somebody that said something to a client of mine.
I've been through a hearing for the state board.
I'm still probably going to end up in a malpractice suit.
The board has fouled me.
And it's because these people talked to some veterinarian somewhere that said something, took it out of context, and made an open comment about something without knowing the whole story.

And this guy, even though the state board has told him that I didn't do anything wrong medically or otherwise, he's still convinced I killed his cat, you know, because of what some other veterinarian said.
And, boy, that just never happened.
It used to happen at all.
It never did in the past.
But it's going to happen in more and more frequency.
Oh, it has happened.
I think that we need to be more aware of our fellow.
I've always adopted the idea and lived with the fact that if I'm a liar, I'm reminding myself.
That's right.
My dad told me a long time ago, if you can't point one finger, somebody else will point three at you.
Well, it's changed like everything's changed.
No, it hasn't.
No, people have.
People have changed.
Yeah.
Individual priorities and so on.
Responsibilities.
Ethics.
Well, okay.
But we have the same thing in a classic example is what we have over there in animal control.
Complete lack of owner responsibility.
Yeah.
Guy comes in, he says, I want to post bail for my dog.
Which dog is yours?
They bring it down.
Is your dog vaccinated?
No.
No.
Well, law, state law, city ordinance says it has to be vaccinated.
Was your dog in his own yard?
Well, no, you picked him up in the street.
And then it's my fault?
I know.
He gets really hostile.
I say, you know, you really need to put a tag on this animal or tattoo him or something because I've been here almost 14 years and I've never had a dog or a cat give me his own phone.
I'm serious.
And we need to tell our clients this.
No, when we came back, when we took state boards.
I never thought about it.
You've made me feel older now.
Rabies was an everyday occurrence.
Yeah, right.
That's true.
Oh, we had tremendous rabies here.
Oh, yeah, it really was.
That's right.
When I came here in 57, this was the rabies capital of the world.
But this was in domestic animals, wasn't it?
It was dogs and cats.
That's right.
But now it's in skunks, bats, foxes, raccoons, very little in dogs.
I mean we've come full circle there again.
It seems to be going back because you're seeing more domestic animals coming out now.
And also we're immunizing fewer and fewer, a smaller percentage of our pet population.
You know, I think historically that's as public awareness drops and the threat drops.
It's happened with measles in kids.
Yeah, that's right.
Then the number of unvaccinated animals goes up and you get a susceptible population and then the scare comes.
The polio in the same way.
Yeah.
Yeah, it's cycling.
And these things should be a thing of the past.
Hooping coughs should be a thing of the past.
Diphtheria should be a thing of the past.
Yeah, but they won't be.
It makes me wonder, you know, are we going to have smallpox again?
How many of these immigrants coming in here?
What in the world are they bringing in?
I know, it makes me shudder.
I've been writing my congressman since I came from Mexico about it.
some of these things.
It's going to fall on deaf ears.
We're going to bring all the Salvadorans in here.
I mean, they need help, and we can take care of them.
They ought to be trying for trees.
Well, I'm taking a lot of your time, but let me give you each one, if you like, a last opportunity to comment.
Well, I was going to tell you what all I had done.
You got married, of course, had a litter of kids.
I was in small animal practice from about 48 to 75.
That's small animal surgery, dentistry, the whole nine yards.
We had a Newcastle disease outbreak about that time, if you recall.
And it just wiped out the chicken population around.
When about 61, 62, somewhere around in there, got involved in pigeons.
My dad used to fly pigeons.
and made contact with a friend of his.
They flew pigeons together before either one of them was married.
And so I kind of allied myself with him.
He was, well, Eddie Hemsworth and Pat Zachary.
Got to working a lot with pigeon parasites.
The foremost of which was his Tetrameres Americana, which just wipes them out.

When birds are called upon to really race a long, hard race, they just can't cut it, because their glandular stomach, their polentriculus, just looks like it's been shot with a shotgun, with these little encased females that burrow into the... And they do lay eggs, and you can demonstrate them on fecals.
And so I was doing a lot of this because these guys were bringing in birds, paying maybe $500, $1,000 a bird.
I saw some, yeah.
Did this also lead to other cage birds?
Well, I did a lot of surgery on birds and did a lot of sterility work on birds.
These guys would say, you know, well...
They'd bring me this hen.
This hen feels like she's normal.
Oh, she lays eggs, but they don't hatch.
Hey, mister, you're going after the wrong bird.
Let's check, you know.
And I used my little hormonal situation.
And I was known as rejuvenating all these old birds.
I mean, just enough to get maybe six or eight youngsters out of them.
And man, then they're happy.
Well.
Did that sustain the pigeon work?
Was that a sustained practice?
It was over a long period of time, yeah, until, well, about 1975.
Well, I was still doing it when I went to work for the city, but not on the biggest scale, because you have to train these birds constantly and drive them.
But I'd worked with Leon Whitney, who was another Auburn graduate.
He had the Huskins Van Rails up in Orange, Connecticut.
And he and I had done some work together.
I mean, I'd done some consultantships and gone and talked to various pigeon groups in South Carolina and also here in California, outside of Ventura.
And then when I got involved in animal control, and by the way, animal control veterinarians are still somewhat of an oddity.
Don't find too many of them.
Well, with the advent of a lot of the humane laws and stuff like that, they're becoming a little more common today than they used to be.
Well, I have a couple of them in Houston.
They have an animal control veterinarian in Dallas.
However, he's not administrating.
Yeah.
I guess Ed Beckham out of Dallas
And, uh, Will Builderback wasn't, um, Lee Hutchison from El Paso.
Bob Ward, who was from Houston.
Same thing in, in research with the, with the humane laws and stuff like that.
Now there's, you know, you, that's the reason I'm still a consultant attorney.
They have very few animals down there, but they do use a few in teaching and research, and so they have to have a veterinarian on there.
on their animal control committee or their animal committee.
Or they can't get any teaching, national NIH teaching funds or research funds or anything.
I'll tell you where we need a veterinarian.
Excuse me.
Go ahead.
Well, I've had a lot to do with parks and wildlife.
I've been on a trip with them to Baja, Mexico eight or nine years ago to capture some desert bighorn.
We shot them with a helicopter.
Somebody just pulled another boo-boo up there.
director it seemed like for some of these wealthy gentlemen.
They just had 40 sheep or something put on a ranch and 39 of them died.
And Gibb Lewis is the Speaker's ranch, yeah.

Those people who make the decisions are usually the guy up here and he doesn't even consult because I went to Baja with him and I talked to, I was one of the two that were not represented and the governor appoints them.
It's too much politics instead of efficiency and animal husbandry and veterinary medicine.
It's sad when you see the results.
Yeah, Parks and Wildlife really should have a veterinary consultant.
They should have a full-time veterinary.
Or a consultant, at least, to the department.
Well, to cover their backsides.
I wrote them.
We had a thing from New Mexico.
They had done the same thing Texas did years ago.
And I told them, I said, you're going to Mexico.
I had lived in Mexico.
And they wouldn't listen.
And they wouldn't listen to their field then.
We lost...
I told them you'd be lucky to get back with half of them.
You're going to stress them.
We got back with about half of them.
Now, this is another example of poor consultation or somebody that they should have listened to.
And some of their own staff even told them.
I don't understand that.
They need someone all the time to put on that board.
They should have one.
Yeah.
I talked to Silber and wrote... At least in a consulting capacity.
Here a few years ago, and the director wrote me a letter, and it was very nice about it.
But still, they don't have a man to consult with on everything.
I mean, you get some variety, some versatility, you get more efficiency.
You've got to have a veteran out there.
They have, what's his name, an A&M?
A parasitologist that used to do a lot of work for parts of my life.
Grimes?
Burley.
No, since I've been in animal control, I've, of course, in the state association and also in the national association, served on executive boards and this, this, and this.
The veterinarians that are involved in that do not accept any elected position except in an advisory capacity for obvious reasons.
That's where I met Ed Beckham and some of the others.
But I've served as a consultant to the UN Development Program of PAHO and, well, Pan American Health Organization, World Health Organization down in Barbados with the Ministry of Health down there.
I've been down there four times.
Designed their euthanasia equipment.
Went back to check on it and then went back four years ago on this to evaluate the overall program again.
What is their problem?
Cats, dogs?
Loose dogs.
Incidentally, I don't know if any of you know, but you might want to support Hawaii in the Humane Society, Hawaiian Humane.
Some veterinarian over there didn't like the idea of having to quarantine a dog for four months, and they're attempting to rescind that law.
I know the state veterinarian, but while you're there, a little personal, there's a cow in the lung.
Is that him?
He's a state governor.
He's active in the A's.
No, this is a woman who took her dog and didn't want to leave the quarantine.
But she tried challenging it in the court system?
Yeah, has gone to pass or has presented a bill to rescind the quarantine.
Oh, in the state legislature.
In the state of Hawaii, yeah.
Because that would be suicide, for God's sake.
I mean, can you imagine if they ever got rapists in the mongoose?
Yeah.
I mean, they're such wonderful little animals in the first place.
No, but Barbados had a problem with dogs, just loose dogs.
The same as, hey, it's international, the irresponsible pet owner.
I mean, the dogs that are running loose are not strays.
They're owned, unvaccinated, free-roaming dogs.
I mean, they've proven that.
These dogs will jump up on a 55-gallon drum and jump and jump until they tip it over, and then screw the garbage.
And, of course, then you have rats.
So we were down there on dog control and rat eradication.
That's where I met Rex from UCAL Davis, Rex Marsh.
And that's another Rex, UCAL Davis.
All I see, we do a consultant work in animal control, go to various cities and troubleshoot their euthanasia units and stuff.
We try awfully hard to acquaint people with the problem.
I mean, PTAs, Rotary Club, Optimist Club, the TVMA.
Tim Long had one of our ACOs down at the convention center when we had the conference here several years ago.

All our ammo control officers in San Antonio are now currently certified by the state as basic ammo control officers, some of them in advanced and some of them in the administrative capacity, and some of them actually in the instructions.
At lunch with Catherine Tull, that's why we turned on to this ammo control bit again.
So what we're trying to do is teach kids the responsibility.
I'm giving up on the adults.
I mean, people our age know what the problem is.
They don't have any experience with animals.
That's right.
They get an animal because the kid pitches it in the mall and they see these precious little puppies.
Okay, we get a little puppy and we take it home.
Forget about the responsibility.
Well, you know, the Humane Movement has missed the boat for
all the years it's been in existence.
You know, they've tried to deal with a problem that was beyond their capability.
I figure you just look at it locally, nationally, and have not attacked the problem from the standpoint of humane education, starting with the kids.
And that's where it has to start.
You know, they've spent millions and millions of dollars trying to find homes for 20% of the dogs and cats that are homeless.
Instead of educating children to try to develop curricula that could be part of every school's curriculum in these kids and develop a humane education.
Well, you know, a pet is a special friend.
If they'd done that 25 years ago, we wouldn't have the problem we have today, certainly on the magnitude of it.
I mean, I think we've reached a state of apathy.
And the next step is back into bondage.
We live in a disposable society.
I keep saying we don't make commitments to ourselves.
If we did, we'd take better care of our bodies.
We wouldn't be overweight, drunk, smoking, all this stuff.
We don't make commitments to our spouses or to our children.
Why wouldn't we make a commitment to an animal?
You're right.
That's a good point.
I got a baby bird that had my office a little...
One week old African gray parrot that has to be fed.
We deal an awful lot with zoonoses.
Boy, you've got to get his 4 o'clock feeding.
I mean, I laugh at everything.
You're cold today, aren't you?
Yeah, I've got to take him home with me tonight.
Everything from Lyme disease to Giardia.
Oh, you did.
I resurrected him from the dead this morning, so I don't want him to die.
Enjoyed it.
It was kind of fun sitting around and talking about it all.
That's why you up there in Pennsylvania, you've got some Amish plants.
My oldest boy is a veteran in Pennsylvania.
And he gets so mad because they won't treat him anymore on Sunday.
And some of them have got to have treatment on Sunday.
I know some veterinarians about that.
Good to see you, Tom.
See you later.
Oh, goodness.
That's a good point about the homeless animal was not the point.
See if I can get a copy of that article that, what was it, Hutton did in the Express last July.
on animal control.
Yeah, if you can throw it up bits and pieces that I can get from you, that would really be helpful.
Because the conversation is very good.
Documentation is, of course, going to help a lot.
Yeah.
But that's the basic, you know, we want everything, but they don't want the responsibility.
That is true in so many things nowadays.
Anyhow, if you ever get fecal contamination and get a Giardia infection, get some medication fast.
Bill McCulloch got it from the
shelter up there, Brazos County Animal Shelter.
He's over there, he's anitizing dogs.

We walk in the kennel in the morning, you know, and they hit the fence like this, and they puddled and spilled their water and defecated in it, and they hit like this, you know, and you're giving it this, and your glasses.
Well, I ended up with Giardia, and I trained myself for about a week.
Don't do it.
I finally went to the doctor.
He won't put me in the hospital.
We did some work with the screw worm problem when we had animals come in to the facility.
Every once in a while I'd run into one that was screw worm positive.
I sent Bucuzum down to mission and I sent a lot of ticks to the lab in Austin and we know that the Lyme disease organism is present in our derma center and Reprocephalus sanguineus, our good old
And then the Lone Star, too, we've identified.
There's going to be a Lyme conference for the benefit of anybody who's interested in Austin in May, 4 and 5.
That's something that's really right on the leading edge of concern right now, the Lyme.
Well, Wiley Tanner, public health veterinarian, was in Austin out of Arlington, had it several years ago.
He's retired now and moved to Colorado.
And I've had this, I guess, for five years now.
To the point now that this eye has deteriorated.
I mean, it just doesn't work by itself.
Is that from Lyme disease?
Apparently, that's what Dr. Schwarting said the other day.
And my husband's pushing me to retire.
I don't know what's down the road for me with this mess, you know?
Are there other cases?
You know, this is another whole area of...
veterinary, you know, the animal bond relationship.
That is the transmission of disease that people are not aware of.
Other than rabies, things like that, we know now.
Well, you try to tell them about T. canis in children, and they look like you're, you know, they're out of your mind.
And yet, out at the medical school, pediatrics will tell you, yeah, we got a problem.
And the physicians and the veterinarians, no, we don't have problems.
It's a problem with that more than we do.
I mean, these little blind kids that run around, I have a great niece that I'm sure they removed her eyes, thought she had retinoblastoma.
I don't think she had retinoblastoma at all.
She ditched that problem with the other eye.
I think she had ticanus, visceral larval migraines.
And hey, down on the beach, that's one of the big things in Barbados, because they're telling them,
Well, you just bury it on the beach.
You don't bury it on the beach.
You just keep bringing it back to you.
And the salt water doesn't do a darn thing.
Well, I think that's about all my notes that I've put down.
If there's notes that are available, I'll take the notes, too.
You want these?
Yeah.
Can I have them?
Yeah.
Oh, I had a poem.
Do you remember that poem, The Piddling Pup?
that Dr. Morney had on his stationery.
Well, I like the title.
Well, it goes on about 10, 12 verses and ends up with Rump had diabetes.
Let me have your address.
Do you have a card?
No, I don't have a card.
Let me just...
I'll tell you, Dr. McCammish had a little thing.
I think it was the creed of the doctor.
And John's daddy was a physician.
Mm-hmm.
And...
I wish every veterinarian had that where he'd see it once in a while.
You know, it states that, you know, your clients are your livelihood, and if they weren't for them, you wouldn't have any income or this and that.
And it makes a lot of people stop and think that they're all going too fast, you know.
I used to go in Johnny's place once in a while and always read that, you know.
Everybody ought to read that.
